  overviewText="Oral cancer has one of the highest survival rates of any cancer when diagnosed at an early stage — and one of the lowest when caught late. The five-year survival rate for early-stage oral cancer is approximately 83%; for cancer that has spread to lymph nodes, it drops to 38%. The challenge is that early oral cancer is frequently asymptomatic — no pain, no visible lump, no obvious sign. That's why professional screening at every dental exam isn't optional: it's the mechanism by which early-stage disease gets caught."
  overviewExtra="At Thrive Dental in Bayside, every comprehensive exam includes a structured oral cancer screening — visual examination of the lips, tongue, floor of the mouth, soft palate, cheeks, and throat, plus tactile palpation of the neck lymph nodes. We supplement this with VELscope fluorescence technology, which causes abnormal tissue to fluoresce differently than healthy tissue under a specific wavelength of light — making lesions visible that are completely invisible to the naked eye in normal light. Patients from Bayside, Whitestone, Fresh Meadows, and Little Neck who smoke, use smokeless tobacco, drink heavily, or have an HPV history should be especially diligent about annual screenings. But because 25% of oral cancers occur in people with no known risk factors, we screen every patient."
